{"title":"MMT-Bench: A Comprehensive Multimodal Benchmark for Evaluating Large Vision-Language Models Towards Multitask AGI","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Current multimodal benchmarks cover few tasks and mostly test rudimentary skills, making them inadequate to track LVLM progress toward multitask AGI across diverse domains and inputs.","method":"Introduce MMT-Bench, a curated benchmark of 31,325 multi-choice visual questions spanning 32 meta-tasks and 162 subtasks across 13 visual input types and multiple modalities (image, text, video, point cloud). It uses a hierarchical task taxonomy, unified metadata, and question/answer generation via manual rules or ChatGPT with hard distractors, while ensuring visual grounding; evaluation follows OpenCompass-style robust answer extraction."},{"problem":"Developers lack a principled way to understand relationships among multimodal tasks, predict performance on new tasks, and identify in-domain vs out-of-domain regions for LVLMs.","method":"Construct a task map by encoding each subtask as a task vector: LoRA-fine-tune a probing LVLM (QwenVL-Chat) per subtask to obtain weight deltas, compute cosine distances, and analyze Kendall’s tau ranking correlations. Hierarchical clustering over this map reveals in-domain clusters (e.g., recognition/description) and out-of-domain clusters (e.g., fine-grained localization, GUI/tables), enabling prediction and targeted improvement."},{"problem":"There is limited, standardized evidence on how prompting strategies (multi-image inputs, coordinate formats, visual referring prompts) impact LVLM performance across heterogeneous tasks.","method":"Within MMT-Bench, evaluate 30 LVLMs under controlled prompting settings: true multi-image vs single-image concatenation on 28 multi-image tasks, visual referring prompts vs text-specified coordinates (normalized vs pixel), and combined modes. Findings show multi-image prompting substantially boosts performance (including for some single-image LVLMs like BLIP2), while pure visual referring prompts generally underperform due to lack of SFT exposure; an expert error taxonomy further characterizes failure modes across models."}]}
